      <hedline>
        <hl1>Jews and Abortion</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>David Zweibel letter disputes Deborah E Lipstadt's August 22 letter, which said Sen Joseph Lieberman's support of Supreme Court's Roe v Wade decision legalizing abortion is only position a traditional Jew can take</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Deborah E. Lipstadt asserts (letter, Aug. 22) that Senator Joseph I. Lieberman's support of Roe v. Wade is the only position that a traditional Jew could take.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Deborah E. Lipstadt asserts (letter, Aug. 22) that Senator Joseph I. Lieberman's support of Roe v. Wade is the only position that a traditional Jew could take.</p>
        <p>Ms. Lipstadt is right that an absolute legislative ban on abortion under any and all circumstances, even in situations where the pregnancy threatens the mother's life, would be unacceptable to observant Jews. She is wrong, though, to assume that the only public policy choices in the area of abortion are all or nothing.</p>
        <p>One can easily conjure a policy that prohibits abortion as a general matter but allows for exceptions in extraordinary cases. Indeed, that is the policy that polls show most Americans support. The abortion-on-demand standard of Roe v. Wade is at fundamental odds with Jewish tradition.</p>
        <p>DAVID ZWIEBEL  New York, Aug. 23, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is executive vice president for government and public affairs, Agudath Israel of America.</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
